{"title":"Reinforcement Learning on Variable Impedance Controller for High-Precision Robotic Assembly","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Tight-tolerance robotic assembly requires precise, contact-aware control, but trajectory-centric RL with direct torque actions struggles to leverage contact constraints and remain stable in free space.","method":"Make the policy’s action an operational-space wrench F_tip and execute it with a hybrid motion/force controller: project desired wrenches to joint torques via J^T pseudoinverse, and wrap with a low-gain position loop with motion/force weightings (Σ1, Σ2) for stability. Train a time-varying linear-Gaussian controller with iLQG (with entropy regularization) to output F_tip conditioned on state. This implicitly yields variable impedance—high impedance in free space and high admittance in contact—while exploiting natural task constraints. On four Siemens assembly tasks it substantially outperforms kinematics and torque-control iLQG baselines (e.g., 5/5 vs 0–1/5 successes on Tasks 1–2)."},{"problem":"Explicitly modeling Pfaffian contact constraints for manipulation is labor-intensive and brittle; controllers need to discover appropriate constraints and compliance from interaction.","method":"Interpret the hybrid operational-space motion/force control with iLQG-learned F_tip as learning Pfaffian constraints A(q), where requested wrenches must lie in Col(A^T(q)), effectively constraining motion/forces at contact without hand-coding. The learned piecewise linear-Gaussian controller adapts compliance across phases, approximating holonomic and nonholonomic task constraints. Empirically, the resulting behaviors align with human heuristics (probing, alignment, force ramping) observed in Tasks 1–3."},{"problem":"Global neural policies for force-based assembly often fail to generalize to small environment changes, and naïvely feeding raw F/T into early layers induces unstable free-space motions due to noise and spurious correlations.","method":"Propose a neural network that low-pass filters wrist force/torque readings and injects them via late fusion at the penultimate layer, keeping early layers primarily state-driven in free space. Train the network with MDGPS to minimize KL divergence to the local iLQG controller (with additional KL constraints), enabling supervised imitation. On base shifts of 1–5 cm, the policy maintains high success (e.g., 9/10 at 1 cm, 8/10 at 2 cm) and dramatically outperforms early-fusion F/T networks (0/10), while slightly improving over iLQG in some settings."}]}
